<p id="comment-truncated-5113-2075027075" class="comment">
Reading Chandra Garsson's notes on &quot;Maya&quot; and &quot;race&quot; got me thinking about the three words I learned in a Sociology class in the 1980s in San Francisco. The teacher (I'll call him &quot;Mr. Chan&quot;) had pulled down a map of the world and said something like:...
</p>
<p id="comment-full-5113-2075027075" class="comment" style="display: none">
Reading Chandra Garsson's notes on &quot;Maya&quot; and &quot;race&quot; got me thinking about the three words I learned in a Sociology class in the 1980s in San Francisco. The teacher (I'll call him &quot;Mr. Chan&quot;) had pulled down a map of the world and said something like: &quot;There are three race classifications.  Caucasoid, Negroid, Mongoloid.&quot;  I heard myself giggling with my fellow-students.  Mr. Chan then pointed at various sections of the map and went on to say that people from Europe were Caucasoids, people from east Asia were Mongoloids, and people in Africa were Negroids.  My parents and their ancestors were from China; that would make me a Mongoloid.  He explained that anthropologists had come up with this classification system based on people's physical characteristics, mainly skin color.<br />
<br />
A student asked: &quot;What about America?&quot;  Mr. Chan (a Mongoloid) answered, &quot; ... indigenous people are Mongoloids and settlers from European countries are Caucasoids.&quot; Then he put his hand on the map, over Mexico. &quot;Negroids,&quot; he said.  &quot;Skin color, other physical features not like Caucasoids' or Mongoloids'.  Mexicans are Negroids.&quot;<br />
<br />
Soon after that day, I was visiting friends; I told them about the three words and how geography played a role in race-labeling.  I repeated what Mr. Chan said about Mexicans. One friend, whose mother's ancestors were from Italy and father's ancestors were from Mexico, exclaimed, &quot;I'm Caucasoid, not Negroid!&quot;<br />
<br />
To this day, my friend's reaction (what race he preferred to be identified with) still surfaces to the foreground of my mind.  I think about how I saw myself when I was a girl. Under my &quot;Mongoloid&quot; features, I wanted to be seen as the blonde-haired actress Sandra Dee because I thought I was just as adorable and kind as the characters she portrayed in movies. Sure, I could have bleached my hair yellow, but that wouldn't have changed the color of my skin, the shape of my eyes, or the width of my nose.  I was never going to be a Caucasoid.<br />
<br />
And why did I want to be one?  Because I saw the way people mistreated my momÂ—-at department stores, at clinics, at the donut shop.  The salespeople would say &quot;thank you&quot; to Caucasoid customers but not to my mother. The receptionists would smile at Caucasoid patients but not at my mom. Their behavior was a contagious disease and I was infected.  The infection caused me to judge everyone, including my mother and myself.  I got all mixed up, believing that only Caucasoids deserved respect.<br />
<br />
In the past thirty years, I have had the fortune of meeting healthy role models (including Chandra of course) who have shown me how to &quot;look&quot; beyond a person's physical attributes.   There are so many dimensions to a personÂ—-including... how he/she treats other people, how he/she expresses his/her passions (whether in painting, writing, gardening, cooking, singing, dancing, playing music, speaking, listening, etc.), what wisdom he/she has gained from ancestors, how he/she solves problems, and what makes him/her joyful.<br />
<br />
Do I still want to look &quot;Caucasoid&quot;?  No, because I understand now that what I had really wanted was to be accepted and appreciated for who I was regardless of what I looked like. <br />
<br />
Chandra, thank you for giving me this opportunity to share my views.  I will be submitting other comments in the months to come.<br />
<br />

</p>
