<p id="comment-truncated-5112-625844365" class="comment">
Maya is the Sanscrit word for illusion, one of the many illusions of this crazed world of ours. My friend, the author Teresa Leyung Ryan, promised she would write on this website if I would begin a blog here on the general subject of 'Race.' Race is...
</p>
<p id="comment-full-5112-625844365" class="comment" style="display: none">
Maya is the Sanscrit word for illusion, one of the many illusions of this crazed world of ours. My friend, the author Teresa Leyung Ryan, promised she would write on this website if I would begin a blog here on the general subject of 'Race.' Race is after all one of the great illusions; I have always believed and said that we as humans have a great deal more in common with one another than have we differences. sadly, probably due to competition, we are hell-bent on continually finding ways to fracture humanity into multiple categories, that being chief among the reasons for so-called racial differences. As an artist I appreciate visually all the rich variation in hair, eye, skin, body, ear, foot, hand, etc. shape, color, texture, and size. That said, as a Jew I have experienced a certain amount personally of what I would call racism. The Clan burnt a cross in front of the house of my mother in rural Colorado, when she was a young child. When I was an adolescent, the vicious boy across the street hung a huge Nazi flag on the garage door where he had a clubhouse for his burgeoning neo-Nazi pals, in full view of our house and the neighborhood. I have heard and felt the pain of many anti-Jewish and other racial slurs throuout my life. My people were almost wiped off the face of the Earth not long ago. For me 'Race' is a long and complicated topic, which I have tried to make short and simple here, to make room for you Teresa, and hopefully you, and you, and you.  
</p>
